06734nam a22008895i 9780520323698DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203236987 a10.1525/97805203236982doi  a(DE-B1597)569866  a(OCoLC)1198929128  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aGN307.7 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a808.066300aCulture/Contexture :bExplorations in Anthropology and Literary Studies /ced. by Jeffrey M. Peck, E. Valentine Daniel.  aReprint 2020 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4cÂ©2023  a1 online resource (420 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tCulture/Contexture: An Introduction -- tPART ONE. Narrative Fields -- t1. The Culture in Poetry and the Poetry in Culture -- t2. The Story of the Jackal Hunter Girl -- t3. Fresh Lima Beans and Stories from Occupied Cyprus -- t4. Narrative Ethnography, Elite Culture, and the Language of the Market -- t5. Exogamous Relations: Travel Writing, the Incest Prohibition, and Hawthorne's Transformation -- t6. The World in a Text: How to Read Tristes Tropiques -- tPART TWO. Identity Markings -- t7. Ethnic Selves/Ethnic Signs: Invention of Self, Space, and Genealogy in Immigrant Writing -- t8. Turks as Subjects: The Ethnographic Novels of Paul Geiersbach -- t9. Narrative, Genealogy, and the Historical Consciousness: Selfhood in a Disintegrating State -- t10. Race and Ruins -- t11. Race under Representation -- tPART THREE. Unsettling Texts -- t12. Reading Culture: Anthropology and the Textualization of India -- t13. Ghostlier Demarcations: Textual Phantasm and the Origins of Japanese Nativist Ethnology -- t14. The Construction of America: The Anthropologist as Columbus -- t15. Crushed Glass, or, Is There a Counterpoint to Culture? -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe rapprochement of anthropology and literary studies, begun nearly fifteen years ago by such pioneering scholars as Clifford Geertz, Edward Said, and James Clifford, has led not only to the creation of the new scholarly domain of cultural studies but to the deepening and widening of both original fields. Literary critics have learned to "anthropologize" their studies--to ask questions about the construction of meanings under historical conditions and reflect on cultural "situatedness." Anthropologists have discovered narratives other than the master narratives of disciplinary social science that need to be drawn on to compose ethnographies. Culture/Contexture brings together for the first time literature and anthropology scholars to reflect on the antidisciplinary urge that has made the creative borrowing between their two fields both possible and necessary. Critically expanding on such pathbreaking works as James Clifford and George Marcus's Writing Culture and Marcus and Michael M. J. Fischer's Anthropology as Cultural Critique, contributors explore the fascination that draws the disciplines together and the fears that keep them apart. Their topics demonstrate the rich intersection of anthropology and literary studies, ranging from reading and race to writing and representation, incest and violence, and travel and time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAnthropology in literature. 0aCriticism. 0aCulture. 0aEthnologyxAuthorship. 0aLiterature and anthropology. 4aCultural Studies. 4aculture. 4aliterary studies. 4aliterature. 4aquestions. 4arace. 4ascience. 4asciences and society. 4asociology of literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aBorneman, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaniel, E. Valentine, 